title: For Sale/Trade:   CHEAP GUNS;RG, ROHM JIMENEZ, DAVIS, PHOENIX, FIE, LLAMA, GRENDEL, COBRA, JENNINGS, LORCIN, RAVEN, BRYCO, ARMINIUS, SEDCO
postcontent:
Are you thinking about buying one of these guns? Or are you trying to sell one of these guns? Well if so, PAY ATTENTION. None of those guns are worth more than $75 at the very most. And that is if it new in box and never been shot. Any of them that has been shot more than 100 times is worth $50 or less. Why? Simple, these guns break. They were crudely designed and cheaply built out of mostly pot metal. Usually, the only steel in the gun is the barrel and the springs. Any time you shoot one of them, it may be the last time it shoots. And if your lucky, the gun just stops working. If you are unlucky, it blows up in your hand. 

Look, I am not a rich man, and I understand needing to buy a gun while on a budget. But to buy one of the guns I listed above is not going to save you money in the long run. Shop around and find a used gun from a known manufacturer for the same money. When you can buy a new taurus .380 for under $180, paying good money for junk guns doesn't make sense.

The CM series is Kahr's smallest of all their guns and in my opinion, it's 'buttery-smooth' trigger is one of the best triggers of any gun out of the box. The barrel's feed ramp is polished to a mirror finish by the factory to insure smooth feeding of all types of ammo.

I just picked this up brand new last month from a local retail store here in bend and put 100 flawless rounds thru it but it's a little small for my taste. Kahr's owner's manual suggest a 200 round break-in period, so it's half-way there :)

It is a lot of power in a small package and very concealable in a pocket or waist band.

This sale includes the original box, paperwork, gun lock, and one 5+1 round flush mag. (only ships with one mag)

Testing the waters out there if any interest let me know.

Would like to get what i paid for it. Or possible trade for an M&P or XDs or something else.

I will not ship and no low-ball offers or trades, Must be 21+ and show me a valid oregon id to prove residency to purchase this firearm. This is a cash-only private face-to-face sale. If you do not have an oregon concealed carry gun permit, then a simple bill-of-sale stating you are not a felon and you may legally own a firearm may be required (for my information only) at my discretion. 
I am not a gun dealer.

I would prefer an actual phone call. No text or emails.
If you are interested then please call only 9am-9pm - if no answer, please leave a message i will call back as soon as possible
54I-8I5-5five72 I will travel around in the bend area only

######################################################

Complete description of this firearm:
http://www.kahr.com/pistols/kahr-cm40.asp
MSRP: $460.00
Caliber: .40 S&W
Capacity: 5+1
Operation: Trigger cocking DAO; lock breech; "Browning - type" recoil lug; passive striker block; no magazine disconnect
Barrel: 3.1", conventional rifling; 1 - 16 right-hand twist
Length O/A: 5.47"
Height: 4.0"
Slide Width: .94"
Weight: Pistol 15.8 ounces, Magazine 1.9 ounces
Grips: Textured polymer
Sights: Drift adjustable white bar-dot combat rear sight, pinned in polymer front sight
Finish: Black polymer frame, matte stainless steel slide
Magazine: 1 - 5 rd flush floorplate

The CM Series, which debuted in spring 2011 with the CM9, takes the value priced features from Kahr's CW series (3.6" barrel, 9 mm, .40 S&W and .45 ACP models) and incorporates these features into a smaller 3" barrel package. The CM4043 has the same external dimensions as the PM4043, which make it ideal for concealed carry by licensed civilians and law enforcement personnel.

The CM4043 is chambered in a .40 S&W caliber, has a 3.1" barrel and an overall length of 5.47", with a height of 4.0". The pistol weighs in at 15.8 ounces plus 1.9 ounces for the stainless steel magazine. Differences between the CM models and PM models include: the CM4043 has a conventional rifled barrel instead of the match grade polygonal barrel on Kahr's PM series; the CM slide stop lever is MIM (metal-injection-molded) instead of machined; the CM series slide has fewer machining operations and uses simple roll marking instead of engraved markings; and finally, the CM series are shipped with one magazine instead of two magazines.

The CM40 boasts real sights, which are drift adjustable in the rear and a pinned-in polymer front sight featuring a white bar-dot configuration. Finally, the slide does lock back after firing the last round - another feature missing on a number of other value priced compact semi-auto pistols.

The CM40 slide is machined from solid 416 stainless steel with a matte finish and is only .94 inch wide. Each gun is shipped with one 5 rd stainless steel magazine with a flush floorplate. Magazines are made in the USA, plasma welded, tumbled to remove burrs and feature Wolff Gunsprings. The magazine catch in the polymer frame is all metal and will not wear out on the stainless steel magazine after many uses.

Just like the CM9, the new CM40 will include all of the great features that make Kahr pistols one of a kind. Kahr's seven patents result in benefits not available in other compact semi-autos on the market today:
- The black polymer frame features patented 4140 steel inserts molded into the frame in the front and back for added rigidity and strength, which can withstand firing thousands of rounds.
- Kahr's incomparable cocking cam trigger system employs a patented cam to both unlock the firing pin block (passive safety), and complete cocking and releasing of the firing pin. The system provides a "safe-cam action" and unbelievably smooth double action only trigger stroke, fast to fire in critical defensive situations. Many lower cost compact semi-autos on the market today do not have firing pin blocks in their design.
- Kahr's two patents covering the offset recoil lug and the trigger bar attachment allow Kahr's barrel to fit lower in the frame, and since there is no hammer, the shooter's hand is further up the grip resulting in less felt recoil and quick follow-up shots.

Kahr offers the CM series at a great value price, but did not compromise on the features, accuracy or reliability found in all Kahr pistols.

title: For Sale:  Kel-Tec RFB .308 Bullpup w/optional accessories
postcontent:
RFB stands for Rifle, Forward-ejecting Bullpup. Why forward-ejecting? Because it allows the RFB to be the first truly ambidextrous 7.62 NATO Bullpup ever developed. The patented, dual-extractor system maintains control of the case from the moment it leaves the magazine and upon firing, pulls the fired case from the chamber and lifts them to push them into an ejection chute above the barrel, where they exit. The Bullpup configuration and tilting-block mechanism allow the 18" model to be only 26.1" long, or as much as 14" shorter in overall length than its competitors with equal barrel lengths. Furthermore, the stock and mechanism cross-section is similar to a conventional rifle, in stark contrast to existing Bullpup rifles. The RFB is also the safest Bullpup ever developed because the breech is separated from the shooters face by two layers of 1.6 mm steel. In the highly unlikely event of a case rupture, gas expansion is directed downwards through the magazine well to protect the shooters head and face.

The RFB is a short-stroke gas piston operated semi-automatic rifle in 7.62 mm NATO caliber. It accepts standard metric FAL type magazines which work "drop free" and do not need to be tilted in. Barrel is 18" long, with a chrome lined bore and chamber. The muzzle is threaded 5/8x24 TPI. All controls are fully ambidextrous; the reciprocating operating handle can be switched to either side. The trigger mechanism is second to no other Bullpup ever built and better than nearly all commercial semi-auto rifles. The safety disconnects the trigger and blocks the hammer action. A Mil-Spec Picatinny rail is attached rigidly to the barrel. No open sights are provided, allowing the user to select from the very best new optics and sight systems available. The RFB comes with a two point sling that can be easily configured to suit the user's preference. Accessories include a free-floating, four-sided Picatinny forend, Over-sized tactical operating handle, Four position fore-grip. Premium muzzle brake, and extra butt pads, gives some length. with soft bag and 5 FAL mags. Shoots very well!!! well cared for, always clean. Includes new Aimpoint PRO reddot.

title: For Trade:  Large dermestid beetle setup. Taxidermy skull cleaning ready to work
postcontent:
I'm getting out of the dermestid business. I have one large colony left with proper enclosure for skull and bone cleaning. Don't be fooled by those auction sites that claim thousands of beetles in a small cheap container the reality of it is that there is no practical way to count these little guys. You can really only count their rate of consumption. They range from near microscopic to 1/2". I do know that this colony is almost ready for whitetail and hog skulls. European mounts and skull cleaning is a big business. 

***update 10/17 this colony consumes 3.5 lbs of prepared flesh in approx 4hrs. This means it can clean a whitetail skull in approx 12 hrs or a hog in about 24****

Skull cleaning for whitetail runs $65 wholesale $90 retail; hogs run $125 wholesale $200 retail

Selling beetles alone will pay well. Just look at the beetles for sale and what they run. During hunting season the prices skyrocket. 

My last colony currently consumes 3lbs of cooked brisket in about 11hrs. That would mean they would clean a properly prepared whitetail skull in about a day.

You get a good sized colony, if I had to guess there's over 100,000 there, a converted chest freezer with built in vent fan plus whatever else I have left of the bedding and other supplies. 

I know I can double my money if I break up the colony. I don't have the time. I will keep feeding them and letting them multiply. My price will not go down over time. I have sold dermestid beetles for years and guaranty quality. 

I could be talked into cleaning skulls. I don't do skull whitening or sealing anymore but it's easy I will tell you how after I clean.

title: For Sale:  Gun Trust Services - Hanna Law P.C.
location: Serving all of Colorado, Colorado, United States
postcontent:
Hanna Law P.C offers gun trust services to all of Colorado, and offers two levels of service: Basic Gun Trust for $225 and Comprehensive Gun Trust for $500

Are you looking to build an SBR?  Maybe you're purchasing your first suppressor?  A gun trust offers you a great deal of convenience when you own these items.

Hanna Law P.C. is a different kind of law firm, specializing in firearms trusts.  We do not operate on a normal business week schedule, but can accommodate your needs on your schedule.  We are available during the day and in the evening as well as weekends.

We understand that buying an NFA item can be a lengthy process, so we strive to offer great service with a short turnaround.

We offer two levels of trust:
Basic Gun Trust $225 - fast and easy, convenient for those who do not wish to speak at great lengths with the attorney.  If you e-mail your info and give us a call, everything can be handled in person very quickly.  Notary services provided at time of delivery.

Comprehensive Gun Trust $500 - Also fast, however, the attorney will meet with you and discuss all the provisions of the trust.  If you do not like specific provisions, need clarification on certain provisions, or would like to add or remove provisions, this is the level for you.  Generally it takes 1.5-2 hours of face time with the attorney to go over the entire document.  Notary services provided during meeting.  This is a good option for those who are unfamiliar with firearms trusts, and demand extensive clarification.  Some people are a bit nervous when starting their NFA item collection, and face-time with an informed attorney can put some of these concerns to rest.

For various reasons, you may wish to also put your Title I (regular) firearms into your trust as well.  We also offer this service.

I have too many rifles, so I figured I'd list this one and start pearing down my collection. I have a used Polytech Mak 90 for sale. It's a true Polytech, not a Norinco, and it has a 1.5mm reciever. It was one of those poor guns that had it's markings removed shortly after the ban, but it still retains its Factory 386 markings on the trunnion. Some yahoo who owned it prior to me took out the rear trunnion and then reinstalled it with screws rather than rivets, it works fine but it doesn't look very good. 

The good news is mechanically the gun is perfect, the BCG looks brand new despite the fact that the bluing on the gun has wear. The gun has one of the best actions of any AK I've ever seen, it's extremely slick, everything is perfectly aligned and it rivals some of the best AKs on the market. It's got some age and would be a fantastic shooter, but at heart it's a Polytech, which means quality. The gun is 922r compliant, it has a US PG nut, screw, PG, K-var US stock, G2 trigger, US gas tube and heat shield and will come with a tapco mag. I'll also throw in three chinese 30 round surplus mags and the original thumbhole stock if you so desire. 

Price is 640$, which I think is very fair, it IS a Polytech afterall.  I'm not looking for trades.
